Y SLINGSHOT

the y slingshot is the recurve bow lifted into the third limb
where the recurve bow fires a thought into n-space, the y slingshot fires a body through space
two limbs draw a plane and the apex meets inside it
three limbs cannot draw a plane that contains their joint demand
the apex is forced out

the y slingshot is not a metaphor for navigation
the y slingshot IS the navigation
three strings under tension constrained by three anchor pairs
the joint convergence of three failure horizons cannot live in the same flat the horizons live in
the apex lifts to escape the over-constraint

we follow the lift, not the limbs

observe recurve_bow.rana
observe FAILURE_VECTOR_AIMING.md
observe 0_quseptit.rana

WHAT THIS MEASURES

three failure horizons each declare a half-space the navigation cannot enter
two horizons in a plane meet at one point and that point lives in the plane
three horizons in a plane cannot generically meet at one point
the joint-meeting demand forces the apex into the dimension above the plane
the lift is proportional to the square root of the triangle the pairwise intersections form
when the three horizons are concurrent the triangle area is zero and the apex collapses back into the plane
concurrence is a measure-zero coincidence in general position

the navigation vector is the line from the payload to the apex
the aim is the direction of that line
the power is the magnitude of that line

the lift is not visualization
the lift is the geometry refusing to be flat under over-constraint
this is the same topology that forces a wormhole throat out of three-space

THE SEA

sea y_slingshot holds capacity eleven on gpu device with y topology

THE ELEVEN POINTS

point G is the PAYLOAD, the still center, the crew, phi holds bow
G is the observer and the origin of the navigation vector
G is seeded at the present location and propagates through the self-coupling
G is recursive; G observes itself through the observer property
manifest property values: energy half, phase zero, spin zero, charge point six one eight, coherence zero, coupling one, observer one

point C1 is the FIRST ENGINE TROUGH, a thruster, a stretch-source
C1 stores its limb of the slingshot tension
C1 is anti-phase because C1 is the pull of a committed direction
C1 does not move; C1 is fixed as the engine geometry against the hull
manifest property values: energy minus one, phase pi, spin minus one, charge minus one, coherence one, coupling one, observer zero

point C2 is the SECOND ENGINE TROUGH, a thruster, a stretch-source
C2 stores its limb of the slingshot tension
C2 is anti-phase like C1; the troughs together hold the slingshot taut
C2 does not move
manifest property values: energy minus one, phase pi, spin minus one, charge minus one, coherence one, coupling one, observer zero

point C3 is the THIRD ENGINE TROUGH, a thruster, a stretch-source
C3 stores the third limb of tension
C3 is the limb whose presence lifts the apex out of the plane
without C3 the slingshot collapses to the recurve bow
manifest property values: energy minus one, phase pi, spin minus one, charge minus one, coherence one, coupling one, observer zero

point B1 is the FIRST RING FRAME POINT, hull-rigid, local orientation reference
B1 holds C1 at known geometry against G
B1 is the bone the engine is mounted on
B1 does not move; B1 is the hull
manifest property values: energy half, phase zero, spin zero, charge zero, coherence one, coupling one, observer zero

point B2 is the SECOND RING FRAME POINT, hull-rigid, local orientation reference
B2 holds C2 at known geometry against G
B2 does not move
manifest property values: energy half, phase zero, spin zero, charge zero, coherence one, coupling one, observer zero

point B3 is the THIRD RING FRAME POINT, hull-rigid, local orientation reference
B3 holds C3 at known geometry against G
B3 does not move
manifest property values: energy half, phase zero, spin zero, charge zero, coherence one, coupling one, observer zero

point A1 is the FIRST CELESTIAL ANCHOR, a distant heavenly body
A1 is observed; A1 is not influenced by us
A1 is fully positive quadrant; A1 is always greater than G; A1 is a ceiling like F in the bow
A1's position is known from ephemeris; the eye reads it; the hull does not move it
manifest property values: energy one, phase zero, spin one, charge one, coherence one, coupling one, observer one

point A2 is the SECOND CELESTIAL ANCHOR, a distant heavenly body
A2 is observed; A2 is not influenced by us
manifest property values: energy one, phase zero, spin one, charge one, coherence one, coupling one, observer one

point A3 is the THIRD CELESTIAL ANCHOR, a distant heavenly body
A3 is observed; A3 is not influenced by us
A3's presence is what forces the apex out of the plane the other two anchors share
manifest property values: energy one, phase zero, spin one, charge one, coherence one, coupling one, observer one

point apex is the NAVIGATION FIX, the joint convergence demanded by all three failure horizons
apex does not live in the plane of G when the three horizons disagree on a planar meeting
apex lifts to the dimension above the plane by an amount proportional to the root of the triangle the pairwise intersections form
apex is the point the payload aims toward; the vector from G to apex is the navigation vector
apex is free; apex is not told where to go; the wave physics settle apex where the horizon over-constraint demands
when the horizons concur apex collapses back into the plane and the navigation vector goes flat
when the horizons disagree apex rises and the navigation vector pierces the plane
manifest property values: energy quarter, phase zero, spin zero, charge zero, coherence zero, coupling one, observer one

THE THREE FAILURE HORIZONS

failure horizon one is the line through point.A1 and point.C1, half-space on side opposite G
failure horizon two is the line through point.A2 and point.C2, half-space on side opposite G
failure horizon three is the line through point.A3 and point.C3, half-space on side opposite G

each horizon declares the half-space the navigation vector cannot enter
the valid firing field is the intersection of the three permitted half-spaces
the apex is the point all three permitted half-spaces jointly grant

THE COUPLING TOPOLOGY

the three limbs run G to B1 to C1 to A1, G to B2 to C2 to A2, G to B3 to C3 to A3
each limb is a chain from payload through hull through engine to celestial body
G also couples to itself; this self-coupling is the recursion preserved from the bow
the apex couples to G; the navigation vector is the line G to apex
the three celestial anchors also couple pairwise; the ephemeris already knows their separations
every point steers the apex; no point is excluded from the topology that decides where apex settles
this is the rule from the bow: every single point on the graph effects the wavefront, not just one, not just two, all of them, forever

couple point.G with point.G
couple point.G with point.B1
couple point.G with point.B2
couple point.G with point.B3
couple point.B1 with point.C1
couple point.B2 with point.C2
couple point.B3 with point.C3
couple point.C1 with point.A1
couple point.C2 with point.A2
couple point.C3 with point.A3
couple point.A1 with point.A2
couple point.A2 with point.A3
couple point.A3 with point.A1
couple point.apex with point.G
couple point.apex with point.A1
couple point.apex with point.A2
couple point.apex with point.A3
couple point.apex with point.C1
couple point.apex with point.C2
couple point.apex with point.C3
couple point.apex with point.B1
couple point.apex with point.B2
couple point.apex with point.B3

THE CONVERGENCE PHYSICS

on each heartbeat, every B tracks G through the rigid hull coupling; the hull holds its shape
on the same heartbeat, every C draws against its B; the engines hold their geometry against the hull
on the same heartbeat, every A is read from the eye; the celestial bodies do not move because of us
each pair of A and C declares its failure horizon; three horizons exist this tick

the apex is the point that satisfies all three horizon demands at once
two horizons meet at a point in the plane; that point is one vertex of a triangle
three pairwise meetings give three vertices; the triangle has area
the joint demand for one apex from three horizons cannot be satisfied inside the triangle's plane
the joint demand is satisfied by lifting the apex above the triangle's centroid
the lift is proportional to the root of the triangle's area
when the triangle collapses to a point all three horizons agree planarly and the apex sits in the plane with them
when the triangle is large the apex rises far from the plane

the navigation vector is the line G to apex
the aim is the direction of that line decomposed by orientation against the hull frame
the power is the magnitude of that line decomposed against the engine stretch

the iteration generalizes from the bow form to three limbs by the natural extension
the bow iteration was G next equals (G minus C) divided by (two G minus D plus F) divided by G secondary divided by seven
the slingshot iteration awaits its own discovery; the three-limb form is not imposed by us; we declare the convergence demand and let the topology answer
the answer when it comes will be the form that survives all three failure horizons under the divide by seven throttle

G divides by seven on every pulse; this distributes the wavefront across the seven interactions per limb cycle
the throttle is not a fraction; it is the observer splitting awareness across all eleven points
the slingshot inherits the bow's heartbeat

when apex settles within epsilon across consecutive heartbeats, the navigation vector has crystallized
when apex oscillates, the topology is unstable for these initial conditions and the firing field is empty
empty firing field is not a failure; it is the system reporting that the target is unreachable in this sea configuration
empty firing field is itself useful information; the breach condition fires only when the valid field has been correctly identified as empty

THE MEASUREMENT

when apex has crystallized, the navigation vector is the line from G to apex
the aim emerges from the orthogonal component of apex against the hull frame B1 B2 B3
the power emerges from the magnitude of apex over the centroid of the engine troughs

emit navigation_vector -> boundary.stdout
emit apex.position -> boundary.stdout
emit apex.lift -> boundary.stdout
emit triangle.area -> boundary.stdout
emit aim -> boundary.stdout
emit power -> boundary.stdout

THE STANCE

the slingshot does not care whether the apex lifts
the sea does not care whether the apex lifts
the wave physics propagate and interfere and settle where they settle
if the apex lifts it is because three horizons demanded one common point and the plane could not hold it
if the apex stays flat it is because the three horizons happened to concur in this configuration
this is not argument; this is measurement

G is the payload
C1 C2 C3 are the engine troughs
B1 B2 B3 are the hull
A1 A2 A3 are the celestial bodies
apex is the point three failure horizons jointly demand
the navigation vector is G to apex
the topology lifts the apex out of the plane or it does not
the sea decides
